benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: PUT /1.0/kb/bundles/{bundleId}/renameKey - Update a bundle externalKey

covered: Valid Request: Happy path and multiple valid payload scenarios (TC01, TC09, TC14, TC21, TC22).
Authentication/Authorization: handling missing/invalid tokens and proper 401/403 responses (TC02, TC12).
Resource existence: proper handling of non-existing resources and no data (TC04, TC15).
Input validation: missing body, malformed JSON, missing externalKey, empty externalKey, malformed bundleId (TC06, TC07, TC08, TC11, TC03).
Conflict and validation: externalKey already in use (TC05).
Edge cases and flexibility: extra fields allowed, special characters, spaces, and boundary lengths (TC09, TC19, TC20, TC10, TC16).
Reliability under failure: service dependency unavailable (TC13).
Headers handling: additional headers like X-Killbill-Reason/X-Killbill-Comment supported (TC14).
No bundles scenario: system with zero bundles (TC15).
Performance: large payloads and response-time checks (TC16, TC23).
Edge: presence of unexpected headers should not fail (TC21).
gaps: Caching behavior: tests for ETag/Cache-Control headers are missing.
Rate limiting: no tests to ensure throttling or quota enforcement.
Internal server error handling: 500 errors beyond 503 not covered.
Boundary conditions beyond 255 characters (e.g., 256+) not explicitly tested.
Explicit test for when externalKey remains unchanged (no-op) not covered.
Stress/concurrency beyond single time window (TC17) not covered; only basic concurrency.
recommendations: Add caching tests (ETag/Cache-Control) to validate caching semantics.
Add rate-limiting tests to verify throttling policies.
Include explicit 500 Internal Server Error scenario (e.g., DB failure) in addition to 503.
Add boundary test for extremely long keys beyond 255 to confirm system limit (256 chars).
Add test for when externalKey equals the current key (no-op) or when renaming to current value; define expected behavior.
Extend concurrency testing with higher load/stress scenarios to observe behavior under heavy contention.
Consider validating that error responses include structured details where applicable.
